Although this is not exactly the typical iris file, Id like to keep the data presented here at least reproducible. You may find the data here:

https://www.kaggle.com/c/titanic/data

test <- read_csv("test.csv") %>% clean_names() %>%
  select(-passenger_id, -name, -ticket, -cabin) %>%
  mutate(female = if_else(sex == "female", 1, 0)) %>%
  select(-sex)

## mutate: new variable 'female' with 2 unique values and 0% NA
## select: dropped one variable (sex)
train <- read_csv("train.csv") %>% clean_names() %>%
  select(-passenger_id, -name, -ticket, -cabin) %>%
  mutate(female = if_else(sex == "female", 1, 0)) %>%
  mutate(survived = as.factor(survived)) %>%
  select(-sex)

Given that this data was downloaded already split from Kaggel, well will obmit this phase of the analysis.

Preprocessing:

titanic_recipe <- train %>%
  recipe(survived ~ .) %>%
  step_dummy(embarked) %>% 
  step_corr(all_predictors()) %>%
  step_center(all_predictors(), -all_outcomes()) %>%
  step_scale(all_predictors(), -all_outcomes()) %>%
  step_bagimpute(age, embarked_Q, embarked_S) %>%
  prep()
## Warning: There are new levels in a factor: NA
titanic_recipe
## Data Recipe
## 
## Inputs:
## 
##       role #variables
##    outcome          1
##  predictor          7
## 
## Training data contained 891 data points and 179 incomplete rows. 
## 
## Operations:
## 
## Dummy variables from embarked [trained]
## Correlation filter removed no terms [trained]
## Centering for pclass, age, sib_sp, parch, fare, ... [trained]
## Scaling for pclass, age, sib_sp, parch, fare, ... [trained]
## Bagged tree imputation for age, embarked_Q, embarked_S [trained]

Prepping the testing data with the same transformations.

test_prepped <- titanic_recipe %>%
  bake(test)

Because the training data was prepped during the making of the recipe, we just need to extract it.

train_prepped <- juice(titanic_recipe)

titanic_logr <- logistic_reg(mode = "classification") %>% 
  set_engine("glm") %>%
  fit(survived ~ ., data = train_prepped)

Now that we have a fairly simple baseline model that performs pretty well, lets jump into some more complicated models.

Random Forest Models

Using the same data as before, well focus on the training data here.

titanic_rf <- rand_forest(trees = 100, mode = "classification") %>%
  set_engine("randomForest") %>%
  fit(survived ~ ., data = train_prepped)

Lets not look at how well xgboost does.

titanic_xg <- boost_tree(mode = "classification", trees = 20) %>%
  set_engine("xgboost") %>%
  fit(survived ~ ., data = train_prepped)
